const faq = [
  { q: `What is a Chinese measure word?`, a: `A measure word (量词, liàngcí) is a classifier placed between a number (or demonstrative like "this/that") and a noun. For example, "one book" is 一本书 (yī běn shū), where 本 is the measure word for books. Unlike English where classifiers are optional, Chinese requires them for every counted noun.` },
  { q: `Can I just use 个 (gè) for everything?`, a: `个 is the most general measure word and native speakers will understand you even if you use it for everything. However, using specific measure words significantly improves your fluency and shows language mastery. In everyday speech, about 70% of nouns can acceptably use 个, but the remaining 30% sound noticeably wrong with 个.` },
  { q: `How many measure words should I learn?`, a: `Chinese has over 100 measure words, but learning the top 20-25 covers approximately 90% of everyday situations. Start with the "essential 12" in this guide, then add 10-15 more as you progress. HSK 4 requires about 30 measure words, and most native speakers actively use 40-50 in daily life.` },
  { q: `Do measure words exist in other languages?`, a: `Yes. Japanese, Korean, Thai, Vietnamese, and many Southeast Asian languages all have classifier systems similar to Chinese. English has partial classifiers: "a piece of paper," "a cup of coffee," "a pair of shoes." The difference is that Chinese requires classifiers for every counted noun, not just some.` },
  { q: `What happens if I use the wrong measure word?`, a: `Using the wrong measure word rarely causes misunderstanding — it sounds odd but the meaning is clear, similar to saying "a piece of book" in English. Native speakers might correct you gently or simply understand what you mean. It is one of those grammar points where getting it right marks the difference between "functional" and "natural" Chinese.` }
